	al (Worry): Your mother has work at the floral shop tomorrow.
	al (Worry): And I have work at the architecture firm in the morning too.
	al (Worry): You need to cut this out right now and just go to sleep.
	al (Worry): I would expect this from Madeline, but not from you Marzi.
	al (Worry): Come on Rosy, Marzi needs to figure this out on her own.
	leave al
	marzi (Dejected): I...I'm sorry...p..lease don't go...
	leave --All--
	(Marzi's parents leave the room and with complicated expressions on their faces, they close the door.)
	(Marzi pulls the covers up over her head and presses her tear stained face into the fabric.)
	(Her mind races and reels and her heart feels like lead in her chest.)
	(Her breathing is shallow and labored.)
	join marzi (Dejected) left
	marzi (Dejected): I...I...I don't know how I could have handled that better.
	marzi (Dejected): Dad was...
	marzi (Hysterical): ...just awful!
	marzi (Hysterical): Th...they ju...st don't g...get it.
	leave marzi
	join marzi (Reeling) left
	marzi (Reeling): (Marzi ruminates for hours, still not fully convinced she's safe and not dying.)
	marzi (Fretfulsleep): (Finally she is so exhausted she falls asleep into fretful dreams.)
	set {tired} = "1"
- Splash ice cold water on my face.
	label prologue_panic_choice_water
	join marzi (Reeling) left
	audio music "res://sounds_music/The_Weight_of_Stillness.mp3"
	marzi (Reeling): (Marzi stumbles out of her bed, her breath coming in ragged hitches.)
	leave marzi
	(She needs to break the spiral before her heart actually leaps out of her chest.)
	(She creeps down the narrow attic stairs, avoiding the creaky third step.)
	(The bathroom is cold, the moonlight reflecting off the porcelain sink.)
	(She remembers her final exam at the confectionery trade school.)
	(She was trying to pull a delicate isomalt ribbon for a sugar sculpture.)
	(The sugar was exactly 160 degrees and her hands began to shake.)
	(A single drop of sweat would have caused the whole showpiece to recrystallize.)
	(Her instructor grabbed her and forced her to dunk her face into the ice bath.)
	join marzi (Resolve) left
	marzi (Resolve): ("If you can't control your own temperature, you'll never control the sugar.")
	(The memory of that freezing water hits her like a physical reset button.)
	(She turns the tap to the coldest setting and cups the water in her trembling hands.)
	(She splashes the ice-cold water onto her face over and over.)
	marzi (Calming): Kaaa~
	(The mammalian dive reflex kicks in, forcing her heart rate to slow down.)
	(System Message\: You have unlocked "Temperature" in Marzi's Skills Toolbox! You can replay this exercise anytime from the Main Menu.)
	marzi (Calming): Phew...that helps a little.
	marzi (Calming): (Marzi looks at herself in the mirror.)
	marzi (Calming): (Beads of water are clinging to her face.)
	marzi (Calming): (She sighs strongly and watches her shoulders loosen and drop.)
	marzi (Calming): Okay, I'm not dying. I'm not having a heart attack.
	marzi (Calming): (She turns off the faucet and heads back up to her bedroom in the attic.)
	marzi (Resolve): Tomorrow is a really important day and I think I'm ready to rest now.
	leave marzi
	join marzi (Sleeping) left
	marzi (Sleeping): (Marzi has a little trouble getting to sleep, but when she does she sleeps soundly and dreamlessly.)
- Put on a guided meditation and breathe.
	label prologue_panic_choice_meditation
	audio music "res://sounds_music/The_Weight_of_Stillness.mp3"
	marzi (Reeling): (Marzi fumbles for her phone, her fingers slick with cold sweat.)
	marzi (Reeling): (She finds the app Chai installed for her last semester.)
	marzi (Reeling): (The interface glows with a soft, pulsing light that mirrors a steady heartbeat.)
	marzi (Reeling): (A calm, recorded voice guides her through placing one hand on her chest.)
	marzi (Reeling): (And the other on her belly.)
	marzi (Meditation): (She closes her eyes and tries to picture Chai standing on the sidelines of the pitch.)
	marzi (Meditation): (He’s always so composed when he’s coaching his soccer team.)
	marzi (Meditation): (He tells his players that if they lose their breath, they lose their focus-)
	marzi (Meditation): (-And if they lose their focus, they lose the game.)
	marzi (Meditation): (He’s going to be such an incredible teacher one day.)
	marzi (Meditation): (In... 2... 3... 4...)
	marzi (Meditation): (Out... 2... 3... 4...)
	marzi (Meditation): (Chai's right... it's just physics... it's just chemistry.)
	(She feels her belly expand and contract like a wave at the beach.)
	marzi (Meditation): (I'm not dying... I'm just breathing.)
	marzi (Meditation): (She imagines the air as a steady, cool tide pulling the heat away from her skin.)
	marzi (Meditation): (Slowly, the tightness begins to unravel like a knot finally loosening.)
	set {panic_points} = "0"
	set {tired} = "0"
	marzi (Meditation): (The rhythm of her breath finally syncs with the pulsing light on her screen.)
	marzi (Restfulsleep): (She drifts off as the heavy static in her mind settles into a soft, quiet hum.)
	marzi (Restfulsleep): (Her dreams are filled with the scent of jasmine and the sun warming her shoulders.)
	(System Message\: You have unlocked "Diaphragmatic Breathing" in Marzi's Skills Toolbox! You can replay this exercise anytime from the Main Menu.)
- Tough it out and just go to bed.
	label prologue_panic_choice_tough
	audio "res://sounds_music/Seven_Seconds_To_Shock.mp3"
	(Marzi squeezes her eyes shut and pulls the thin quilt up to her chin.)
	(Her heart is still thudding against her ribs like a trapped bird.)
	marzi (Dejected): (Just stop. Just stop. It's fine. Everything is fine.)
	marzi (Dejected): (She tries to force her muscles to go limp, but her shoulders are hiked up to her ears.)
	marzi (Dejected): (The silence of the attic feels heavy, pressing down on her chest until it hurts to inhale.)
	marzi (Dejected): (She thinks about the boutique receipt, the empty savings account, and Madame Beatrix’s cold eyes.)
	marzi (Dejected): (Every time she almost drifts off, a fresh jolt of adrenaline snaps her eyes wide open.)
	marzi (Exhausted): I can't afford to be this tired tomorrow. I have to work.
	marzi (Exhausted): (She stares at the dark ceiling, her mind spinning in a loop of 'what-ifs' and 'should-haves'.)
	marzi (Exhausted): (The 'toughing it out' feels less like strength and more like a slow, exhausting endurance test.)
	marzi (Fretfulsleep): (Hours bleed into each other, the gray moonlight shifting across the floorboards.)
	marzi (Fretfulsleep): (By the time her eyes finally stay shut, the birds outside are already starting their pre-dawn chatter.)
	set {panic_points} += "5"
	set {tired} = "1"
- Name five things.
	label prologue_panic_choice_5things
	audio music "res://sounds_music/The_Weight_of_Stillness.mp3"
	(Marzi presses her hands flat against the floorboards, letting the solid surface anchor her.)
	marzi (Breathing): Okay. 5-4-3-2-1. Just like Chai showed me.
	marzi (Breathing): He always said this works anywhere. In this dusty attic, or wherever you happen to be right now.
	marzi (Breathing): Let's do it together. Look around the room.
	marzi (Breathing): Five is sight. Let's look for a specific color. What are five yellow things you can see nearby?
	[text_input text="Type five yellow things you see:" var="thing_1"]
	marzi (Calming): {thing_1}. Right. That's real. That's right in front of us.
	marzi (Breathing): Four is touch. Reach out your hand. What are four things with a distinct texture that you can physically feel?
	[text_input text="Type four things you can touch:" var="thing_2"]
	marzi (Breathing): {thing_2}. Focus on how solid those are.
	marzi: Three is sound. Listen closely, past the quiet. What are three sounds you can hear happening right now?
	[text_input text="Type three sounds you can hear:" var="thing_3"]
	marzi (Calming): {thing_3}. Just normal, everyday sounds. The world is still turning.
	marzi: Two is smell. This one is always tricky. Breathe in. What are two scents you can smell, or really comforting ones you can imagine?
	[text_input text="Type two scents you can smell or imagine:" var="thing_4"]
	marzi (Calming): {thing_4}. I can almost smell it too. That helps.
	marzi (Breathing): One is taste. What is a flavor you can taste right now, or your absolute favorite flavor to remember?
	[text_input text="Type one flavor:" var="thing_5"]
	marzi (Calming): {thing_5}. Perfect.
	(The heavy, crushing weight in her chest finally begins to unravel.)
	marzi (Restfulsleep): (She takes one last, deep breath, letting the quiet rhythm of the night finally lull her to sleep.)
	set {panic_points} -= 10
	(System Message\: You have unlocked "Name 5 Things" in Marzi's Skills Toolbox! You can replay this exercise anytime from the Main Menu.)
- Double check my bank app.
	label prologue_panic_choice_bank
	audio music "res://sounds_music/Seven_Seconds_To_Shock.mp3"
	(Marzi grabs her phone from the nightstand, squinting against the harsh glare of the screen.)
	marzi (Reeling): (Maybe dad looked at an old statement. Maybe some of the graduation money is still there.)
	marzi: (Just one or two hundred. Just enough so I'm not completely at zero.)
	(She opens the banking app, her thumb hovering over the screen as the little loading circle spins.)
	(The glowing logo pulses, each second dragging out into an eternity.)
	(The dashboard finally refreshes, the numbers snapping into place.)
	(Her dad’s printout was outdated, but not in the way she hoped. The final pending charges from the boutique just cleared.)
	(Available Balance\: -300G)
	(And right beneath it, a fresh line item in stark, glaring red\: OVERDRAFT FEE -35G)
	marzi (Bank Account): No. No, no, no.
	marzi: (They hit me with a fee. I don't even have zero. I have less than zero.)
	(She aggressively swipes down to refresh the page again, her hands shaking so badly she almost drops the device.)
	(The red numbers refuse to budge.)
	(She drops the phone onto the quilt like it burned her, the screen still glowing with her massive mistake.)
	(A sudden, freezing rush of adrenaline floods her veins, making her fingertips go entirely numb.)
	(Her throat tightens up, the air in the cramped attic suddenly feeling impossibly thick and useless.)
	marzi: (I spent it all. I spent money I didn't even actually have on clothes I can't even wear to work.)
	marzi: (Why did I buy all those stupid dresses? I didn't need any of that stuff. I was just stressed and wanted to feel better.)
	marzi: (And now it's gone. All of it. For nothing.)
	(She pulls her knees tight against her chest, wrapping her arms around her legs so hard her joints ache.)
	(Every frantic pulse of her heart thuds against her eardrums, deafening in the quiet room.)
	marzi: (If my parents find out I overdrew my account before I even moved out, they're going to completely lose it.)
	marzi: (Dad is going to do that horrible, quiet sigh, and Mom is going to scream about how I can never do anything right.)
	marzi: (They’ll tell me I'm totally irresponsible and not ready for the real world. And they'll be right.)
	(A sharp wave of nausea rolls through her stomach, twisting it into tight knots.)
	marzi: (The first month's rent at the new place is covered, but what about month two?)
	marzi: (I have to pay the bank back, somehow buy groceries, and make rent starting from negative three hundred and thirty-five gold?)
	marzi: (I'm going to be evicted. I haven't even moved in and I'm already going to be homeless.)
	(The slanted ceiling of the attic seems to press downward, trapping her in the dark.)
	(She squeezes her eyes shut, but the glowing red numbers are burned into the back of her eyelids.)
	(There is no escape from the physical weight crushing her chest, no rational thought that can pierce through the deafening rush of terror.)
	(She spends the rest of the night shivering under the thin blanket, staring blankly at the wall as her mind cycles through every catastrophic failure waiting for her.)
	(By the time the gray morning light bleeds through the tiny window, she hasn't closed her eyes for a single second.)
